The gentle breeze, as we shall learn (^Purg.~ XXVIII.85-87),
surprises Dante, who had expected to find no meteorological disturbance
of any kind in the garden.  It strikes upon his brow, perhaps reminding
us that that was where the seven P's were inscribed on him by the
warder of the purgatorial gate (^Purg.~ IX.112).  He is, as was Adam
when he found himself in this place 6,499 years ago (see ^Par.~
XXVI.119-123), innocent.  Unlike Adam, Dante will not fall in it.
