Insisting again on the slowness, and thus the calm, of his
progress (see ^Purg.~ XXVIII.5), Dante implicitly contrasts his
entrance into the world of sin in the first canto of the poem with his
arrival in the garden.  Here, just as there, he takes stock by looking
back through a wood toward his point of entrance: 'How I came there I
cannot really tell, / I was so full of sleep / when I forsook the one
true way' (^Inf.~ I.10-12), but the differences between the two places
overwhelm their similarities.
The phrase ^selva antica~ (ancient forest) possibly reflects, as
commentators, beginning with Tommaseo (comm. to these verses) have
suggested, ^Aeneid~ VI.179: 'itur in antiquam silvam' (they move into
the ancient forest).  Virgil is speaking of Aeneas and his men, engaged
in cutting down trees for the funeral pyre of Misenus, and the forest
is that at Cumae, where Aeneas will shortly find the golden bough that
will allow him to enter the underworld.
