This stream is Lethe, the river of oblivion in classical
literature, in which Christians in Dante's Eden leave the memory of
their sins behind them for eternity, as Matelda will explain (vv.
127-128).  For this river Tommaseo (comm. to these verses) cites
Virgil, ^Georgics~ IV.19: 'tenuis fugiens per gramina rivus' (a slender
stream stealing through the grassy field).  Virgil is describing an
appropriate spot in which to set up a hive in order to make honey.
