With regard to the word ^rido~: Matelda is probably not
laughing, as some hold, but smiling; see Bernhard K,onig ("Canto
XXVIII," in ^Lectura Dantis Turicensis: Purgatorio~, ed. Georges
G,untert and Michelangelo Picone [Florence: Cesati, 2001]), p. 441,
citing ^Convivio~ (III.viii.1) for a smile as the shining forth of
delight in the soul.
