The protagonist's series of smiles (beginning at ^Purg.~
XXI.109), caused by his pleasure in the prospect of the joy that
Statius will experience once he discovers that he is in the company of
Virgil, is now matched by the two smiling countenances of those two
poets as they understand, through Matelda's 'corollary,' that they have
finally found the true Golden Age.
